User: Build a single page Next.js frontend using the App Router and Tailwind CSS only.
No component libraries. This is a demo — keep it clean and readable, not elaborate.

Layout: One page. A form section at the top, results section below that appears after 
submission. The form needs a large textarea for the legal question, a state dropdown 
pre-filled with a detected state and a small label indicating it was auto-detected from 
the network, an optional smaller textarea for pasting a contract clause or facts, a 
toggle for including bills alongside cases, and a submit button with a loading state.
The results section renders only when a response is returned and should show the issue 
summary, a list of authority cards each with the title, why it is pertinent, and a link 
to the source, the fact sensitive considerations as a simple list, and the coverage note 
at the bottom in muted text.

API connection: All fetch calls go through a Next.js API route at /api/analyze that 
proxies to the Backend. The route should extract the real client IP from request headers 
and forward it with the request body. The Backend URL comes from an environment variable 
and is never exposed to the browser.

State detection: On page load call the Backend to get the default state from the user's 
IP and pre-fill the dropdown. Show a small badge next to the selector that reads 
"Detected from network" until the user manually changes it, at which point it disappears.

Error and loading states: Disable the form during submission. Show a simple loading 
indicator on the button. If the Backend returns an error or no results, show a plain 
inline message — no modals or complex UI.

Types: Define all shared TypeScript interfaces in a single lib/types.ts file matching 
the BriefResponse schema from the API contracts documentation. Components never call 
fetch directly — all network calls go through a single lib/api.ts file.

